			<description>---Quote (Originally by gorhil, original dev of microblock)--- 
The more you give, the more many act as if you owed them even more. This  is what ground me down in the long run. If the project has any  intrinsic value, it will survive. The move was a huge relief for me. I  have been postponing this...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			<div>
				Originally Posted by <strong>gorhil, original dev of microblock</strong>
				
			</div>
			<div class="message">The more you give, the more many act as if you owed them even more. This  is what ground me down in the long run. If the project has any  intrinsic value, it will survive. The move was a huge relief for me. I  have been postponing this for long now, thinking things might improve.  They did not, from my point of view.</div>
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div>Source: <a href="http://www.wilderssecurity.com/threads/ublock-a-lean-and-fast-blocker.365273/page-33#post-2476324" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.wilderssecurity.com/threa...3#post-2476324</a><br />
<br />
There are a ton of similarities between being a Guild Leader in a MMORPG and being a project maintainer, completely thankless job nearly always. The amount of shit that is necessary to put up with is absurd. I think the most exceptional example is either the PHP mailing list. It's like a really aggressive, hostile instance of bikeshedding except the people rarely can actually build the bikeshed they are being belligerent over. It's worth keeping a product closed simply to avoid dealing with the clusterfuck.</div>

