			<title>Anime you should watch: Kill la Kill</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?77743-Anime-you-should-watch-Kill-la-Kill&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Sun, 29 Mar 2015 04:58:07 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I'm not sure how many people are left who care about anime on this forum, and anyone who does should already know about this one, but I (late to the party) just got around to watching this and thought it was amazing enough to deserve a thread. 
 
One sentence sell on this anime: it's from the...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I'm not sure how many people are left who care about anime on this forum, and anyone who does should already know about this one, but I (late to the party) just got around to watching this and thought it was amazing enough to deserve a thread.<br />
<br />
One sentence sell on this anime: it's from the people who made Gurren Lagann. It came out and blew up over the internet about a year ago, i think, but I ignored it for a few reasons, including not liking the weird fan servicey character designs. Well shame on me for doubting these guys, because the show is fantastic. <br />
<br />
I'll also go ahead and say that there are many styles of anime that can appeal to different people's tastes, but this is not the kind I would recommend to people who don't already like anime. Like Gurren Lagann, you will appreciate it more the more you have been exposed to other anime, specifically of the genre it represents. <br />
<br />
Where Gurren Lagann was both a parody and a celebration of giant robot anime, Kill la Kill is a parody and a celebration of transformation warrior anime, for lack of a better genre label. It's all about shows where the characters power up and transform into ridiculous outfits to battle each other. As I said, I reacted negatively to these designs, but after having given it a chance realize that it's part of the genius of their take on the genre.<br />
<br />
I don't want to give too much credit to the explanations, as bullshitting contrived justifications for fanservice by itself isn't remarkable in the least, I think it's the how itself that makes the show special. Most of the time it seems less like an attempt to be alluring and more like a joke instead. It is also gender neutral, as one of the central male characters has a habit of getting more and more naked the longer he monologues, culminating in a couple purple lens flare effects that can change position for the sake of comedy. Of course, it could be said that I only find it mild because of how ridiculous and blatant it is in other anime these days, but most of it still seems fairly benign to me. <br />
<br />
That's not the only convention of the genre that the show parodies. Another example is how every transformation or special attack is accompanied by large red kanji characters that sometimes become physical objects in the world itself, complete with their own shadows. It's great.<br />
<br />
<br />
So what is the show itself about? Ryuko returns home to find her father brutally murdered and goes on a quest to find the killer. She finds herself at an academy run by a dictator named Satsuki who looks down on human beings in general. The academy itself produces school uniforms made of a special material that enhances the wearer's abilities, and Ryuko finds she is no match for them, only to discover a similar power her father left behind for her. She also befriends the school slacker, who contributes to a fair amout of the comedic relief of the show, and 90% of all internet gifs of the show. She's a goofball and it's great.<br />
<br />
The show deals in themes related to clothing and the &quot;sin&quot; of nakedness. It's also got some of the stylish music and fight scenes you would expect.<br />
<br />
So in short, if you liked Gurren Lagann then you should watch this. If you haven't seen Gurren Lagann, you should watch that, then watch this. <br />
<br />
I watched it in Japanese, but here is the English trailer, along with one of my favorite character themes. One of the things I like about anime is the way specific music can be overlaid with exposition to make a scene seem more dramatic, and this was the best one for that. Be careful of spoilers if you open these in youtube itself though.<br />
<br />

<iframe class="restrain" title="YouTube video player" width="640" height="390" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/pLhE2EhuoZ8?wmode=opaque" frameborder="0"  allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen  mozallowfullscreen ></iframe>
<br />
<br />

<iframe class="restrain" title="YouTube video player" width="640" height="390" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/FRivqBxbHRs?wmode=opaque" frameborder="0"  allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen  mozallowfullscreen ></iframe>
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
On a side note, I don't watch tv anymore, but checked out Adult Swim at a relative's house and was amazed at how much anime they had on. It was technically Toonami, but I remember getting new anime on the network used to be so rare that they would make fun of it in their commercial breaks.<br />
<br />
They had Kill la Kill, Deadman Wonderland (good for few episodes, but doesn't really go anywhere), Attack on Titan, Sword Art Online, a new Inuyasha, Naruto, etc. I think I would personally still just recommend streaming that stuff, as I don't see any point in watching something in three months that you can watch in one week, but I was still impressed.</div>

